			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Ok, I guess that asserting two different rows in the dram close enough in time allows charges to be passed from the first row to the second. <br />Looking at the schematics the dram is organized in 32 rows and 8 columns for OAM (plus 1 column for secondary OAM). <br />If the active row(the one OAM points to) is refreshed every clock cycle, and the row is changed very close to the end of the refresh cycle the charges left in the lines should be able to pass over to the now active line.<br /><br />I did some more testing in Visual 2c02, now looking at the lines activating the rows, and it seems at the start of rendering, the active row which OAMADDR points to is cleared before it would normally and the address line to the row where 0x20-0x27 is present is activated for what remains of the cycle.<br /><br />After that secondary OAM clear starts (although not writing anything since it is the prerender line), also offset to the same row as 0x20-0x27 so OAM2 clear starts at byte 4 instead of 0.<br /><br />Isn't it possible that this is not a timing related issue, but some logic error in the simulator setting the address line to row 4 instead of 0 at the start of rendering? Since it always seems to be the case in the simulator that OAM2 starts to clear at byte 4 instead of 0 on the pre-render line.<br /><br />Anyway, the simulator is awesome. Really helps for figuring out detailed behavior for my emulator development.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

